dataset.abstract: Study locations across Queensland have been visited since 1982 to collect data on physical and vegetation features, including structural and floristic attributes well as descriptions of its landscape, soil and geologic features. The resulting site database provides a comprehensive record of areas ground-truthed during the mapping process and a basis for future updating of mapping or other relevant work such as species modelling. The CORVEG study locations are primarily used for ground-truthing and validating of Regional Ecosystems (RE) mapping, and describing and classifying vegetation mapping units. (http://www.ehp.qld.gov.au/ecosystems/biodiversity/regional-ecosystems/technical_descriptions.html). Please use the following URL to access the dataset: http://aekos.org.au/collection/qld.gov.au/corveg

methodStep.description: Study Location Selection Method: This method is applied to identify study locations suitable for repeatable vegetation assessments. Study locations are selected to ensure that all vegetation and regional ecosystems are adequately sampled across their geographic range. Allocation of study locations should be generally proportional to the area of each vegetation type, except for rare vegetation types. The study locations are distributed in such a way as to sample as much as possible the environmental variability across the landscape, given the time and accessibility constraints. The total number of study locations depends on the variability in the vegetation, the amount of remnant vegetation present and the number of existing study locations in adjoining regions. While study locations are located to describe typical examples of each vegetation and aerial photo-pattern type, care is taken to sample the full range of variation within a vegetation association or regional ecosystem. The general location of each site is predetermined in the office through preliminary stratification using geology, forestry, topographic and rainfall maps as well as Landsat satellite images and aerial photographs. However, it can sometimes be necessary to relocate a study location when it is first visited because of accessibility problems, disturbance to the site or if the stand area is found to be less than 1 hectare. Furthermore, additional sites can be established if variations to the preliminary stratification are encountered during initial visit to the study location. ; Study Location Establishment Method: This method is carried out during the initial site visit in order to establish a study location for repeatable assessments of vegetation and physical features. The study location is established during the first visit to the study location prior to conducting the assessment of the study location features. In order to physically establish the study location and prepare it for the subsequent assessments, the field observers record its geographic location and select a 50m x 10m quadrat within the study location. This sampling quadrat will be used to carry out the physical and vegetation assessments. ; Study Location Visit Method: The study location visit method is undertaken when carrying out a visit to a site encompassing sampling and observation of vegetation and physical features by applying repeatable methods. Once the Study Location Establishment Method has been completed, field observers implement the observations and measurements of ecological features. Two types of study location visits are carried out in the scope of CORVEG, featuring different details of data collection during the vegetation and physical assessment: secondary and tertiary visits.The study location visit triggers subsequent methods for assessments of physical and vegetation features of the study location. ; Landscape Assessment Method: The landscape assessment method is undertaken in order to describe the features of the landscape present at and around the study location. At each visit to the study location, the landscape features are re-assessed. The field observers visually assess landform pattern, landform element, landform context, topographical position and relief. Furthermore, slope and aspect are measured, and the altitude is derived from a topographic map. ; Structural Formation Assessment Method: The structure of the predomininant vegetation layer of the sampling unit is described by selecting a suitable structural formation value. Additional structural features of rainforest canopies are also recorded. The structural formation classification is based on Specht (1970). The predominant layer is characterised as having the highest above-ground biomass, regardless of its canopy cover. The structural formation type of the vegetation is determined by its indicator growth form, height and crown cover/projective foliage cover. In addition, for rainforest plots, structural complexity, leaf size, floristic composition and deciduousness are recorded. Vegetation Community Assessment Method: To describe structure and species composition of the vegetation community present at and around the study location. A description of the vegetation community characterising the study location is recorded. It is determined by identifying the predominant species and vegetation structure of the study location. If appropriate, associated environmental context is also assessed, for example landform geology can be included in the description of the vegetation community (e.g. Eucalyptus crebra with occasional Corymbia erythrophloia open-woodland and grassy ground layer on low hills derived from basalt). The community area and, for linear communities, the width are determined by estimating the pre-clearance extent of the vegetation community in the immediate area that the site represents. This extent is derived from observations made when travelling to and from the site or aerial imagery at the time of sampling. ; Vegetation Structural Summary Method: To assess the height, cover, canopy density and abundance for each stratum, and basal area, stem density and crown cover for targeted species. For each visit to the sampling unit, the observer divides the vegetation into strata and assesses canopy density, canopy height, crown cover and absolute abundance for each stratum. Basal area, stem density and crown cover for each individual species are also recorded. Depending on the type of floristic sampling applied for the study location visit, either all species (secondary study location visits) or all woody species and the dominant non-woody species (tertiary study location visits) are assessed both for the individual observations and for determining the attributes per stratum. ; Disturbance Assessment Method: The method is carried out to assess the evidence of disturbances which have occurred previously within the sampling unit. The observer visually assesses the evidence of disturbances which have occurred prior to the visit to the study location. The type of disturbance, the time elapsed since the disturbance are recorded as well as the severity of the disturbance within the sampling unit. ; Soil Assessment Method: The soil assessment method is carried out to classify the surface colour and surface texture of the soil within the sampling unit using a soil map, cutting (i.e. soil exposed through earthworks), soil core or surface observation. The soil type within the plot is assessed through visual inspection of a cutting (i.e. soil exposed through earthworks), a soil core or inspection of the soil surface and using soil maps. A HERBRECS (The Queensland Herbarium Records System) soil type is recorded to represent the soil within the sampling unit. The observer also assigns classifications for surface soil colour and surface texture to describe the soil. A reliability measure for assessment of the different soil features is recorded to capture if the soil has been examined by an experienced pedologist or specialist. In addition, a specific soil type is identified following the Australian Soil Classification (Isbell, 2002) if a detailed soil site is established. ; Ground Cover Assessment Method: This method is carried out to characterise the proportion of the soil surface covered by different cover types. The share of the soil surface within the sampling unit covered by bare ground, rock, litter and cryptogams is visually estimated. ; Geology Assessment Method: The geology assessment method is carried out in order to determine the geological features of the study location. The geological features are assessed either using a geological map, a core or evaluating an outcrop. The lithology type, the reliability of the assessment and the source of the geological information are recorded. The assessment is usually undertaken at the study location but it can sometime be carried out in an adjacent area (e.g. at a quarry or other exposed rock face).
